<poem>
<title poet="Spencer_A">Letters to My Sister</title>
    
      <stanza>
<l n="1">It is dangerous for a woman to defy the gods<punc type="semicolon">; </punc></l>
<l n="2"><figLang form="metaphor">To taunt them with the tongue's thin tip</figLang><punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
<l n="3"><figLang form="metaphor">Or strut in the weakness of mere humanity</figLang><punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
<l n="4"><figLang form="metaphor">Or draw a line daring them to cross</figLang><punc type="semicolon">;</punc> </l>
 <l n="5">The gods own the searing lightnin<punc type="comma">g,</punc></l>
<l n="6">The drowning waters<punc type="comma">,</punc> tormenting fears</l>
<l n="7">And <figLang form="personification">anger of red sins</figLang><punc type="period">. </punc></l>
      </stanza>
<stanza>
<l n="8">Oh, but worse still if you mince timidly--</l>
      <l n="9">Dodge this way or that, or kneel or pray<punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
       <l n="10">Be kind, or sweat agony drops</l>
        <l n="11">Or lay your quick body over your feeble young<punc type="semicolon">;</punc></l>
       <l n="12">If you have beauty or none<punc type="comma">,</punc> if celibate</l>
     <l n="13">Or vowed--the gods are Juggernaut<punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
     <l n="14">Passing over . . . over . . .</l>
       </stanza>
        
        <stanza>
          <l n="15">This you may do<punc type="colon">:</punc></l>
        <l n="16">Lock your heart<punc type="comma">, </punc>then<punc type="comma">, quietly,</punc></l>
       <l n="17">And lest they peer within<punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
        <l n="18">Light no lamp when dark comes down</l>
       <l n="19">Raise no shade for sun<punc type="semicolon">;</punc></l>
        <l n="20">Breathless must your breath come through</l>
        <l n="21">If you'd die and dare deny</l>
        <l n="22">The gods their god-like fun<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
       
        </stanza>
    </poem>

    

